    # === SURVIVAL GUIDES (16) ===
    ("Emergency USB Toolkit", "emergency-usb.html",
     '''Build a multi-boot emergency USB drive for system rescue, diagnostics, and recovery.''',
     "Survival", "fas fa-suitcase-medical", [
        Q("Choosing Your USB", '''<p>USB 3.0+ 64GB+ drive recommended. Brands: SanDisk, Samsung, Kingston durable models. Label and store in a safe place. Ventoy is the best tool: install once, then simply drop .iso files onto the drive. Boot order: set USB first in BIOS (F2/F12/Del on boot). UEFI vs Legacy: most modern systems use UEFI — ensure your rescue ISOs support it. Secure Boot: disable in BIOS if some tools won't boot.</p>'''),
        Q("Essential Rescue ISOs", '''<p>Essential ISOs for your emergency USB: Hiren's Boot CD PE (Windows PE with tools), SystemRescue (Linux rescue environment), Ubuntu Desktop/Mint (full Linux desktop), GParted Live (partition management), Memtest86+ (RAM testing), Clonezilla (disk imaging). Boot all ISOs at least once at home — nothing worse than a non-booting USB in an emergency. Update ISOs every 6 months (distros release security patches).</p>'''),
        Q("Portable Apps to Include", '''<p>In addition to ISOs, keep portable app packages: antivirus (Malwarebytes, Emsisoft Emergency Kit), data recovery (Recuva, TestDisk/PhotoRec), password tools (chntpw, Ophcrack), network tools (Wireshark portable, PuTTY, FileZilla), browsers (Firefox Portable with extensions), encryption (VeraCrypt Portable). Organize in folders on the drive's remaining space. Create a README.txt with tool descriptions and instructions.</p>'''),
    ],[F("Ventoy","https://www.ventoy.net/","Multi-boot USB tool"),F("Hiren's Boot CD","https://www.hirensbootcd.org/","Windows PE rescue environment")]),
    ("Emergency Prep Checklist", "emergency-prep-checklist.html",
     '''A step-by-step checklist to prepare your digital life for emergencies — before disaster strikes.''',
     "Survival", "fas fa-list-check", [
        Q("Digital Prep Checklist", '''<p>Monthly: backup critical files (cloud + local), update emergency USB ISOs, test VPN connection, verify backups are restorable. Quarterly: update password manager vault, review 2FA recovery codes, check emergency contacts in Bitwarden/LastPass, test system restore points. Annually: replace aging USB drives (they wear out), update Kiwix ZIM archives, review digital will/emergency access setup, practice restoring from backup.</p>'''),
        Q("Physical Prep", '''<p>Print and store in a fireproof safe: 2FA recovery codes for every account, password manager master password, bank helpline numbers, insurance policy details, VPN provider credentials, emergency contact list. USB drives: two copies — one in your bag (daily carry), one in a safe (home). Encrypt with VeraCrypt (container or full disk). Label everything clearly — "EMERGENCY USB — [DATE]" with a list of contents on the label.</p>'''),
        Q("Communication Plan", '''<p>Emergency communication: agree on a family communication tree (who calls whom), set up a Signal group chat for urgent notifications, share location via Google Maps/Signal, keep a prepaid phone for emergencies (always charged). Offline comms: install Briar (Bluetooth mesh), set up Meshtastic nodes if available, learn basic HAM radio (technician license is easy to obtain). Dead drop: agreed-upon physical location for USB swaps.</p>'''),
    ],[F("Ready.gov","https://www.ready.gov/kit","US emergency preparedness guide"),F("Digital Emergency Kit Guide","https://digitalemergencykit.com/","Comprehensive digital prep")]),
    ("Essential Rescue Tools", "tools.html",
     '''Curated list of essential offline rescue tools for every scenario.''',
     "Survival", "fas fa-tools", [
        Q("Top 10 Must-Have Tools", '''<p>1. Hiren's Boot CD PE (Windows rescue), 2. Ventoy (multi-boot USB), 3. Kiwix + ZIM archives (offline Wikipedia), 4. VeraCrypt (full-disk encryption), 5. KeePassXC (offline passwords), 6. Clonezilla (disk imaging), 7. TestDisk/PhotoRec (data recovery), 8. Malwarebytes (malware removal), 9. Process Explorer/Autoruns (Sysinternals), 10. Signal (encrypted comms). These ten cover 95% of emergency scenarios from system failure to security breach.</p>'''),
        Q("Tool Selection by OS", '''<p>Windows: Sysinternals Suite (Process Explorer, Autoruns, TCPView), NirSoft utilities (password recovery, network monitoring), Hiren's Boot CD PE. Linux: ddrescue (data recovery), fsck (filesystem repair), systemd journalctl (log analysis), htop/btop (process monitoring), netstat/ss (network). Cross-platform: VeraCrypt, KeePassXC, WireGuard, Firefox, VLC, 7-Zip, Python (for custom scripts). Keep both 32-bit and 64-bit versions.</p>'''),
        Q("Building Your Kit", '''<p>Build your kit in stages. Stage 1 (basic): 64GB USB with Ventoy, Hiren's Boot CD, Ubuntu ISO, portable apps. Stage 2 (intermediate): add SystemRescue, Memtest86, GParted, Clonezilla. Stage 3 (advanced): add network equipment (spare router, Ethernet cables, Wi-Fi adapter), SBC (Raspberry Pi with pre-configured SD card), LoRa radio (Meshtastic). Stage 4 (complete): multiple USBs (different OS rescue versions), external backup drive, offline maps, printed documentation.</p>'''),
    ],[F("Sysinternals Suite","https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/","Windows system utilities"),F("NirSoft","https://www.nirsoft.net/","Windows password and network tools")]),
    ("Setting Up Offline Servers", "servers.html",
     '''Run local servers for offline use — DHCP, DNS, file sharing, and media streaming without internet.''',
     "Survival", "fas fa-server", [
        Q("Local Network Services", '''<p>Offline servers run on a LAN without internet. DHCP server: assign IPs automatically (dnsmasq or your router), DNS server: resolve local hostnames (dnsmasq with /etc/hosts or Pi-hole), NTP server: keep devices' clocks synchronized (chrony). File sharing: Samba (Windows file shares), NFS (Linux), SFTP/SSH (cross-platform). Media streaming: Jellyfin (open-source Plex alternative) serves your movie/TV/music library offline.</p>'''),
        Q("Raspberry Pi as Server", '''<p>Raspberry Pi 4/5: the perfect offline server. Power consumption: ~5W (runs 24/7). Services to run: Pi-hole (DNS-level ad blocking and caching), Samba (file server with external HDD), Jellyfin (media server with hardware transcoding on Pi 5), Syncthing (offline file sync between devices), Kiwix-serve (serve ZIM content over LAN). Install with Raspberry Pi OS Lite (no desktop — saves resources). Use PoE (Power over Ethernet) for single-cable deployment.</p>'''),
        Q("Mesh Networking", '''<p>When infrastructure fails, mesh networks keep devices connected. BATMAN-adv: kernel-level mesh protocol for Wi-Fi — nodes relay data for each other. Yggdrasil: IPv6 mesh network with end-to-end encryption — auto-configures, can route over the internet too. CJDNS: encrypted IPv6 mesh. Setup: flash LibreMesh on compatible routers (TP-Link, Ubiquiti), configure mesh interfaces, and deploy multiple nodes for coverage. Each new node strengthens the network.</p>'''),
    ],[F("Raspberry Pi Documentation","https://www.raspberrypi.com/documentation/","Official Pi setup guides"),F("LibreMesh","https://libremesh.org/","Open-source mesh networking firmware")]),
